WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:02.440
The ribosome, who I mentioned a little while back,

00:02.440 --> 00:05.360
can make an elephant one molecule at a time.

00:05.360 --> 00:07.200
Ribosomes are slow.

00:07.200 --> 00:09.240
They run at about one molecule a second.

00:09.240 --> 00:11.480
But ribosomes make ribosomes.

00:11.480 --> 00:14.520
So you have trillions of them, and that makes an elephant.

00:14.520 --> 00:16.640
In the same way, these little assembly robots,

00:16.640 --> 00:20.280
I'm describing, can make giant structures at heart

00:20.280 --> 00:23.240
because the robot can make the robot.

00:23.240 --> 00:26.760
So more recently, two of my students, Amira and Miana,

00:26.760 --> 00:29.200
had a nature communication paper showing

00:29.240 --> 00:33.760
how this robot can be made out of the parts it's making

00:33.760 --> 00:35.520
so the robots can make the robot,

00:35.520 --> 00:38.160
so you build up the capacity of robotic assembly.

00:40.360 --> 00:43.520
The following is a conversation with Neil Gershenfeld,

00:43.520 --> 00:46.720
the director of MIT's Center for Bits and Atoms,

00:46.720 --> 00:49.880
an amazing laboratory that is breaking down boundaries

00:49.880 --> 00:52.560
between the digital and physical worlds,

00:52.560 --> 00:56.880
fabricating objects and machines at all scales of reality,

00:56.920 --> 00:59.920
including robots and automata

00:59.920 --> 01:02.240
that can build copies of themselves

01:02.240 --> 01:06.600
and self-assemble into complex structures.

01:06.600 --> 01:09.400
His work inspires millions across the world

01:09.400 --> 01:13.240
as part of the maker movement to build cool stuff,

01:13.240 --> 01:18.240
to create the very act that makes life so beautiful and fun.

01:19.920 --> 01:21.880
This is a Lex Friedman podcast.

01:21.880 --> 01:23.840
To support it, please check out our sponsors

01:23.840 --> 01:25.000
in the description.

01:25.000 --> 01:28.520
And now, dear friends, here's Neil Gershenfeld.

01:29.520 --> 01:31.880
You have spent your life working at the boundary

01:31.880 --> 01:36.200
between bits and atoms, so the digital and the physical.

01:36.200 --> 01:38.960
What have you learned about engineering

01:38.960 --> 01:43.240
and about nature of reality from working at this divide,

01:43.240 --> 01:45.040
trying to bridge this divide?

01:45.040 --> 01:48.760
I learned why Van Neumann and Turing

01:48.760 --> 01:51.260
made fundamental mistakes.

01:52.260 --> 01:55.780
I learned the secret of life.

01:55.780 --> 01:57.180
Yeah.

01:57.180 --> 02:01.100
I learned how to solve many of the world's most important

02:01.100 --> 02:03.300
problems, which all sound presumptuous,

02:03.300 --> 02:05.460
but all of those are things I learned at that boundary.

02:05.460 --> 02:07.700
Okay, so Turing and Van Neumann, let's start there.

02:07.700 --> 02:09.820
Some of the most impactful, important humans

02:09.820 --> 02:12.620
who have ever lived in computing, why were they wrong?

02:12.620 --> 02:16.220
So, I worked with Andy Gleason,

02:16.220 --> 02:17.740
who is Turing's counterpart.

02:17.740 --> 02:20.140
So, just for background, if anybody doesn't know,

02:20.140 --> 02:22.140
Turing is credited with the modern architecture

02:22.140 --> 02:25.900
of computing, among many other things.

02:25.900 --> 02:28.380
Andy Gleason was his US counterpart.

02:28.380 --> 02:31.660
And you might not have heard of Andy Gleason,

02:31.660 --> 02:33.940
but you might have heard of the Hilbert problems.

02:33.940 --> 02:36.380
And Andy Gleason solved the fifth one.

02:36.380 --> 02:39.460
So, he was a really notable mathematician.

02:39.460 --> 02:41.340
During the war, he was Turing's counterpart.

02:41.340 --> 02:43.980
Then Van Neumann is credited with the modern architecture

02:43.980 --> 02:47.780
of computing, and one of his students was Marvin Minsky.

02:47.860 --> 02:50.140
So, I could ask Marvin what Johnny was thinking,

02:50.140 --> 02:52.940
and I could ask Andy what Alan was thinking.

02:52.940 --> 02:55.300
And what came out from that,

02:55.300 --> 02:58.060
what I came to appreciate as background,

02:58.060 --> 03:00.540
I never understood the difference between computer science

03:00.540 --> 03:01.900
and physical science.

03:01.900 --> 03:05.900
But Turing's machine, that's the foundation

03:05.900 --> 03:10.180
of modern computing, has a simple physics mistake,

03:10.180 --> 03:13.020
which is the head is distinct from the tape.

03:13.020 --> 03:14.860
So, in the Turing machine, there's a head

03:14.860 --> 03:17.540
that programmatically moves and reads and writes a tape.

03:17.540 --> 03:19.180
The head is distinct from the tape,

03:19.180 --> 03:22.060
which means persistence of information

03:22.060 --> 03:25.140
is separate from interaction with information.

03:26.220 --> 03:30.140
Then Van Neumann wrote deeply and beautifully

03:30.140 --> 03:32.700
about many things, but not computing.

03:32.700 --> 03:36.780
He wrote a horrible memo called the first draft

03:36.780 --> 03:38.660
of a report on the EDVAC,

03:38.660 --> 03:41.980
which is how you program a very early computer.

03:41.980 --> 03:46.060
In it, he essentially roughly took Turing's architecture

03:46.060 --> 03:47.620
and built it into a machine.

03:48.700 --> 03:53.580
So, the legacy of that is the computer somebody's using

03:53.580 --> 03:55.900
to watch this is spending much of its effort

03:55.900 --> 03:59.620
moving information from storage transistors

03:59.620 --> 04:01.380
to processing transistors,

04:01.380 --> 04:04.060
even though they have the same computational complexity.

04:04.060 --> 04:08.460
So, in computer science, when you learn about computing,

04:08.460 --> 04:10.900
there's a ridiculous taxonomy

04:10.900 --> 04:15.100
of about a hundred different models of computation.

04:15.140 --> 04:16.860
But they're all fictions.

04:16.860 --> 04:20.340
In physics, a patch of space occupies space.

04:20.340 --> 04:23.420
It stores state, it takes time to transit,

04:23.420 --> 04:24.780
and you can interact.

04:24.780 --> 04:28.140
That is the only model of computation that's physical.

04:28.140 --> 04:30.300
Everything else is a fiction.

04:30.300 --> 04:34.820
So, I really came to appreciate that a few years back

04:34.820 --> 04:36.460
when I did a keynote for the annual meeting

04:36.460 --> 04:38.500
of the supercomputer industry,

04:38.500 --> 04:40.500
and then went into the halls and spent time

04:40.500 --> 04:42.300
with the supercomputer builders,

04:42.300 --> 04:45.580
and came to appreciate,

04:45.580 --> 04:48.020
oh, let's see, if you're familiar with the movie,

04:48.020 --> 04:52.140
The Metropolis, people would frolic upstairs in the gardens,

04:52.140 --> 04:54.540
and down in the basement, people would move levers.

04:54.540 --> 04:58.140
And that's how computing exists today,

04:58.140 --> 05:00.740
that we pretend software is not physical.

05:00.740 --> 05:02.620
It's separate from hardware.

05:02.620 --> 05:05.020
And the whole canon of computer science

05:05.020 --> 05:06.700
is based on this fiction

05:06.700 --> 05:09.580
that bits aren't constrained by atoms,

05:09.580 --> 05:12.700
but all sorts of scaling issues in computing

05:12.700 --> 05:13.740
come from that boundary,

05:13.740 --> 05:16.780
but all sorts of opportunities come from that boundary.

05:16.780 --> 05:18.740
And so, you can trace it all the way back

05:18.740 --> 05:22.060
to Turing's machine making this mistake

05:22.060 --> 05:23.220
between the head and the tape.

05:23.220 --> 05:28.220
Van Neumann, he never called it Van Neumann's architecture.

05:28.220 --> 05:30.180
He wrote about it in this dreadful memo,

05:30.180 --> 05:31.260
and then he wrote beautifully about

05:31.260 --> 05:32.900
other things we'll talk about.

05:32.900 --> 05:36.500
Now, to end a long answer, Turing and Van Neumann

05:36.500 --> 05:38.140
both knew this.

05:38.180 --> 05:41.900
So all of the canon of computer scientists credits them

05:41.900 --> 05:45.300
for what was never meant to be a computer architecture.

05:45.300 --> 05:48.300
Both Turing and Van Neumann ended their life

05:48.300 --> 05:52.300
studying exactly how software becomes hardware.

05:52.300 --> 05:55.300
So Van Neumann studied self-reproducing automata,

05:55.300 --> 05:58.420
how a machine communicates its own construction.

05:58.420 --> 06:00.580
A Turing studied morphogenesis,

06:00.580 --> 06:02.340
how genes give rise to form.

06:02.340 --> 06:06.140
They ended their life studying the embodiment of computation,

06:06.140 --> 06:09.140
something that's been forgotten by the canon of computing,

06:09.140 --> 06:10.900
but developed sort of off to the sides

06:10.900 --> 06:12.940
by a really interesting lineage.

06:12.940 --> 06:16.260
So there's no distinction between the head and the tape,

06:16.260 --> 06:17.940
between the computer and the computation.

06:17.940 --> 06:19.500
It is all computation.

06:19.500 --> 06:22.860
Right, so I never understood the difference

06:22.860 --> 06:25.540
between computer science and physical science.

06:25.540 --> 06:29.060
And working at that boundary helped lead to things

06:29.060 --> 06:31.100
like my lab was part of doing

06:31.100 --> 06:32.780
with a number of interesting collaborators,

06:32.780 --> 06:36.580
the First Fest or the classical quantum computations.

06:36.580 --> 06:39.340
We were part of a collaboration creating

06:39.340 --> 06:40.900
the minimal synthetic organism

06:40.900 --> 06:42.740
where you design life in a computer.

06:42.740 --> 06:45.500
Those both involve domains

06:45.500 --> 06:48.420
where you just can't separate hardware from software.

06:48.420 --> 06:51.180
The embodiment of computation is embodied

06:51.180 --> 06:52.900
in these really profound ways.

06:54.220 --> 06:56.860
So the first quantum computations,

06:56.860 --> 07:00.540
synthetic life, so in the space of biology,

07:00.540 --> 07:02.740
the space of physics at the lowest level

07:02.740 --> 07:05.740
and space of biology at the lowest level.

07:05.740 --> 07:09.260
So let's talk about CBA, Center of Bits and Atoms.

07:09.260 --> 07:12.940
What's the origin story of this MIT, legendary MIT center

07:12.940 --> 07:16.300
that you're a part of creating?

07:16.300 --> 07:19.780
In high school, I really wanted to go to vocational school

07:19.780 --> 07:24.100
where you learn to weld and fix cars and build houses.

07:24.100 --> 07:27.180
And I was told, no, you're smart, you have to sit in a room.

07:27.180 --> 07:28.380
And nobody could explain to me

07:28.380 --> 07:31.380
why I couldn't go to vocational school.

07:32.380 --> 07:35.140
I then worked at Bell Labs,

07:35.140 --> 07:39.460
this wonderful place before deregulation, legendary place.

07:39.460 --> 07:41.820
And I would get union grievances

07:41.820 --> 07:43.980
because I would go into the workshop

07:43.980 --> 07:45.380
and try to make something and they would say,

07:45.380 --> 07:48.700
no, you're smart, you have to tell somebody what to do.

07:48.700 --> 07:52.220
And it wasn't until MIT, and I'll explain how CBA started,

07:52.220 --> 07:55.580
but I could create CBA that I came to understand

07:55.580 --> 07:58.100
this is a mistake that dates back to the Renaissance.

07:58.100 --> 08:01.900
So in the Renaissance, the liberal arts emerged

08:01.900 --> 08:04.420
and liberal doesn't mean politically liberal.

08:04.420 --> 08:07.580
This was the path to liberation, birth of humanism.

08:07.580 --> 08:10.380
And so the liberal arts were the trivium, quadrivium,

08:10.380 --> 08:12.900
roughly language, natural science.

08:12.900 --> 08:17.900
And at that moment, what emerged was this dreadful concept

08:19.020 --> 08:20.580
of the illiberal arts.

08:20.580 --> 08:22.580
So anything that wasn't the liberal arts

08:22.580 --> 08:25.540
was for commercial gain and was just making stuff

08:25.580 --> 08:28.500
and wasn't valid for serious study.

08:28.500 --> 08:31.780
And so that's why we're left with learning to well

08:31.780 --> 08:34.140
wasn't a subject for serious study,

08:35.100 --> 08:37.420
but the means of expression have changed

08:37.420 --> 08:38.340
since the Renaissance.

08:38.340 --> 08:41.900
So micromachining or embedded coding

08:41.900 --> 08:44.420
is every bit as expressive as painting a painting

08:44.420 --> 08:45.460
or writing a sonnet.

08:45.460 --> 08:49.420
So never understanding this difference

08:49.420 --> 08:52.020
between computer science and physical science,

08:53.020 --> 08:58.020
the path that led me to create CBA with colleagues

08:58.140 --> 09:01.900
was, I was what's called the junior fellow at Harvard.

09:01.900 --> 09:04.220
I was visiting MIT through Marvin

09:04.220 --> 09:05.740
because I was interested in the physics

09:05.740 --> 09:07.020
of musical instruments.

09:08.540 --> 09:10.900
This will be another slight digression.

09:10.900 --> 09:13.820
And Cornell, I would study physics

09:13.820 --> 09:15.660
and then I would cross the street

09:15.660 --> 09:17.540
and go to the music department where I played the bassoon

09:17.540 --> 09:19.460
and I would trim reads and play the reads

09:19.460 --> 09:21.860
and they'd be beautiful, but then they'd get soggy.

09:21.860 --> 09:23.340
And then I discovered in the basement

09:23.340 --> 09:26.140
of the music department at Cornell was David Borden,

09:27.140 --> 09:28.260
who you might not have heard of,

09:28.260 --> 09:30.180
but is legendary in electronic music

09:30.180 --> 09:32.380
because he was really the first electronic musician.

09:32.380 --> 09:36.180
So Bob Mogue, who invented Mogue synthesizers

09:36.180 --> 09:39.420
was a physics student at Cornell like me crossing the street

09:39.420 --> 09:41.140
and eventually he was kicked out

09:41.140 --> 09:42.860
and invented electronic music.

09:42.860 --> 09:45.540
David Borden was the first musician

09:45.540 --> 09:47.060
who created electronic music.

09:47.060 --> 09:49.020
So he's legendary for people like Phil Glass

09:49.020 --> 09:50.460
and Steve Reich.

09:50.580 --> 09:52.940
And so that got me thinking about,

09:52.940 --> 09:55.620
I would behave as a scientist in the music department,

09:55.620 --> 09:57.900
but not in the physics department,

09:57.900 --> 09:59.260
but not in the music department,

09:59.260 --> 10:00.100
got me thinking about

10:00.100 --> 10:03.820
what's the computational capacity of a musical instrument.

10:03.820 --> 10:07.140
And through Marvin, he introduced me to Todd Backover

10:07.140 --> 10:08.860
at the Media Lab,

10:08.860 --> 10:11.660
who was just about to start a project with Yo-Yo Ma

10:11.660 --> 10:15.180
that led to a collaboration to instrument a cello,

10:15.180 --> 10:17.300
to extract Yo-Yo's data

10:17.300 --> 10:20.300
and bring it out into computational environments

10:20.300 --> 10:23.420
what is the computational capacity of a musical instrument?

10:23.420 --> 10:24.740
As we continue on this tangent

10:24.740 --> 10:26.180
and we'll share a return to CBA.

10:26.180 --> 10:31.180
Yeah, so one part of that is to understand the computing

10:33.020 --> 10:36.100
and if you look at like the finest timescale

10:36.100 --> 10:38.540
and length scale you need to model the physics,

10:38.540 --> 10:39.980
it's not heroic.

10:39.980 --> 10:42.900
A good GPU can do teraflops today.

10:42.900 --> 10:45.020
That used to be a national class supercomputer,

10:45.020 --> 10:46.300
now it's just a GPU.

10:46.300 --> 10:48.940
And that's about if you take the timescales

10:48.940 --> 10:50.700
and length scales relevant for the physics,

10:50.700 --> 10:53.380
that's about the scale of the physics computing.

10:53.380 --> 10:55.780
For Yo-Yo, what was really driving it

10:55.780 --> 10:59.500
was he's completely unsentimental about the Strad.

10:59.500 --> 11:02.180
It's not that it makes some magical wiggles

11:02.180 --> 11:03.380
in the sound wave,

11:03.380 --> 11:05.940
it's performance as a controller,

11:05.940 --> 11:09.860
how he can manipulate it as an interface device.

11:09.860 --> 11:11.500
Interface between one and what exactly?

11:11.500 --> 11:12.820
Him and sound.

11:12.820 --> 11:13.660
Okay, him and sound.

11:13.660 --> 11:15.700
And so what it led to was,

11:15.700 --> 11:18.020
I had started by thinking about ops per second,

11:18.020 --> 11:23.020
but Yo-Yo's question was really resolution and bandwidth.

11:23.140 --> 11:27.220
It's how fast can you measure what he does

11:27.220 --> 11:32.220
and the bandwidth and the resolution

11:32.900 --> 11:36.220
of detecting his controls

11:36.220 --> 11:38.420
and then mapping them into sounds.

11:38.420 --> 11:41.740
And what we found, what he found was

11:41.740 --> 11:44.140
if you instrument everything he does

11:44.140 --> 11:46.940
and connect it to almost anything,

11:46.980 --> 11:48.620
it sounds like Yo-Yo,

11:48.620 --> 11:51.220
that the magic is in the control,

11:51.220 --> 11:55.780
not in ineffable details in how the wood wiggles.

11:55.780 --> 11:59.060
And so with Yo-Yo and Todd, that led to a piece in,

11:59.060 --> 12:00.140
towards the end I asked Yo-Yo,

12:00.140 --> 12:02.860
what it would take for him to get rid of his Strad

12:02.860 --> 12:03.820
and use our stuff?

12:03.820 --> 12:05.460
And his answer was just logistics.

12:05.460 --> 12:09.140
It was at that time, our stuff was like a rack of electronics

12:09.140 --> 12:12.620
and lots of cables and some grad students to make it work.

12:12.620 --> 12:16.140
Once the technology becomes as invisible as the Strad,

12:16.380 --> 12:19.100
then sure, absolutely he would take it.

12:19.100 --> 12:22.060
And by the way, as a footnote on the footnote,

12:22.060 --> 12:25.140
an accident in the sensing of Yo-Yo's cello

12:25.140 --> 12:27.820
led to $100 million a year auto safety business

12:27.820 --> 12:29.860
to control airbags and cars.

12:29.860 --> 12:31.260
How did that work?

12:31.260 --> 12:34.020
I had to instrument the bow without interfering with it.

12:34.020 --> 12:38.100
So I set up local electromagnetic fields

12:38.100 --> 12:42.780
where I would detect how those fields interact

12:42.780 --> 12:45.380
with the bow he's playing.

12:45.380 --> 12:47.540
But we had a problem that his hand,

12:47.540 --> 12:49.660
whenever his hand got near the sensing fields,

12:49.660 --> 12:51.060
I would start sensing his hand

12:51.060 --> 12:53.580
rather than the materials on the bow.

12:53.580 --> 12:57.500
And I didn't quite understand what was going on

12:57.500 --> 13:00.180
with that interference.

13:00.180 --> 13:04.940
So my very first grad student ever, Josh Smith,

13:04.940 --> 13:07.420
did a thesis on tomography with electric fields,

13:07.420 --> 13:10.380
how to see in 3D with electric fields.

13:10.380 --> 13:13.380
Then through Todd and at that point,

13:13.380 --> 13:15.740
research scientist in my lab, Joe Paradiso,

13:15.740 --> 13:18.460
it led to a collaboration with Penn and Teller,

13:18.460 --> 13:21.820
who, where we did a magic trick in Las Vegas

13:21.820 --> 13:23.100
to contact Houdini.

13:23.100 --> 13:25.780
And sort of these fields are sort of like,

13:25.780 --> 13:27.140
contacting spirits.

13:28.260 --> 13:30.500
So we did a magic trick in Las Vegas.

13:30.500 --> 13:33.620
And then the crazy thing that happened after that

13:33.620 --> 13:37.820
was Phil Rittmueller came running into my lab.

13:37.820 --> 13:42.180
He worked with, this became with Honda and NEC,

13:42.220 --> 13:45.700
airbags were killing infants in rear-facing child seats.

13:45.700 --> 13:49.540
Cars need to distinguish a front-facing adult

13:49.540 --> 13:52.540
where you'd save the life versus a bag of groceries

13:52.540 --> 13:53.940
where you don't need to fire the airbag

13:53.940 --> 13:56.300
versus a rear-facing infant where you would kill it.

13:56.300 --> 13:58.820
And so the seat need to, in effect,

13:58.820 --> 14:01.140
see in 3D to understand the occupants.

14:01.140 --> 14:05.100
And so we took the Penn and Teller magic trick

14:05.100 --> 14:08.620
derived from Josh's thesis from Yo-Yo's cello

14:08.620 --> 14:10.060
to an auto show.

14:10.060 --> 14:11.100
And all the car companies said,

14:11.140 --> 14:12.820
great, when can we buy it?

14:12.820 --> 14:15.900
And so that became Elisys and it was $100 million a year

14:15.900 --> 14:17.700
business making sensors.

14:17.700 --> 14:19.060
There wasn't a lot of publicity

14:19.060 --> 14:22.180
because it was in the car so the car didn't kill you.

14:22.180 --> 14:24.500
So they didn't sort of advertise,

14:24.500 --> 14:26.780
we have nice sensors so the car doesn't kill you.

14:26.780 --> 14:28.900
But it became a leading auto safety sensor.

14:28.900 --> 14:30.580
And that started from the cello

14:30.580 --> 14:33.260
and the question of the computational capacity,

14:33.260 --> 14:34.180
the musical instrument.

14:34.180 --> 14:35.020
Right.

14:35.020 --> 14:39.340
So now to get back to MIT,

14:39.340 --> 14:42.260
I was spending a lot of outside time at IBM research

14:42.260 --> 14:45.100
that had gods of the foundations of computing.

14:46.260 --> 14:48.220
There's just amazing people there.

14:48.220 --> 14:52.300
And I'd always expected to go to IBM to take over a lab.

14:52.300 --> 14:57.100
But at the last minute, pivoted and came to MIT

14:57.100 --> 15:02.100
to take a position in the media lab

15:02.500 --> 15:05.460
and start what became the predecessor to CBA.

15:05.500 --> 15:09.940
Media lab is well known for Nicholas Negarpanti.

15:09.940 --> 15:13.460
What's less well known is the role of Jerry Wiesner.

15:13.460 --> 15:15.740
So Jerry was MIT's president

15:15.740 --> 15:17.540
before that Kennedy science advisor,

15:17.540 --> 15:20.140
grand old man of science.

15:20.140 --> 15:21.740
At the end of his life,

15:21.740 --> 15:25.940
he was frustrated by how knowledge was segregated.

15:25.940 --> 15:28.220
And so he wanted to create a department

15:28.220 --> 15:30.140
of none of the above,

15:30.140 --> 15:33.540
a department for work that didn't fit in departments.

15:33.580 --> 15:37.100
And the media lab in a sense was a cover story

15:37.100 --> 15:38.660
for him to hide a department.

15:39.740 --> 15:42.300
As MIT's president towards the end of his tenure,

15:42.300 --> 15:44.100
if he said, I'm gonna make a department

15:44.100 --> 15:45.660
