47:28.000 --> 47:32.160
but it really didn't fundamentally change.

47:32.160 --> 47:36.040
The core things happened in that transition

47:36.040 --> 47:37.300
in the mini computer era.

47:37.300 --> 47:40.200
So in the same sense, the research now,

47:40.200 --> 47:41.360
we spent a while talking about

47:41.360 --> 47:43.680
is how we get to the replicator.

47:43.680 --> 47:46.640
Today you can do all of that if you close your eyes

47:46.640 --> 47:49.140
and view the whole fab lab as a machine.

47:49.140 --> 47:51.080
In that room, you can make almost anything,

47:51.080 --> 47:52.800
but you need a lot of inputs.

47:52.800 --> 47:55.680
Bit by bit, the inputs will go down

47:55.680 --> 47:57.440
and the size of the room will go down

47:57.440 --> 47:59.880
as we go through each of these stages.

47:59.880 --> 48:04.720
So how difficult is it to create a self-replicating assembler,

48:04.720 --> 48:09.720
self-replicating machine that builds copies of itself

48:09.720 --> 48:11.680
or builds more complicated version of itself,

48:11.680 --> 48:14.360
which is kind of the dream towards which you're pushing

48:14.360 --> 48:16.880
in a generic arbitrary sense?

48:16.880 --> 48:20.360
I had a student Nadia Peek with Jonathan Ward,

48:20.400 --> 48:23.600
who for me started this idea of how do we use

48:23.600 --> 48:26.800
the tools in my lab to make the tools in the lab?

48:26.800 --> 48:29.520
In a very clear sense,

48:29.520 --> 48:31.840
they are making self-reproducing machines.

48:31.840 --> 48:34.560
So one of the really cool things that's happened

48:34.560 --> 48:38.040
is there's a whole network of machine builders

48:38.040 --> 48:38.920
around the world.

48:38.920 --> 48:41.800
So there's Danielle and now in Germany

48:41.800 --> 48:43.120
and Jens in Norway.

48:43.120 --> 48:48.120
And each of these people has learned the skills

48:48.800 --> 48:50.920
to go into a fab lab and make a machine.

48:50.920 --> 48:54.040
And so we've started creating a network of super fab,

48:54.040 --> 48:55.520
so the fab lab can make a machine,

48:55.520 --> 48:56.520
but it can't make a number

48:56.520 --> 48:58.680
of the precision parts of the machine.

48:58.680 --> 49:01.960
So in places like Bhutan or Kerala in the south of India,

49:01.960 --> 49:04.000
we've started creating super fab labs

49:04.000 --> 49:06.800
that have more advanced tools to make the parts

49:06.800 --> 49:09.280
of the machines so that the machines themselves

49:09.280 --> 49:11.240
become even cheaper.

49:11.240 --> 49:15.680
So that is self-reproducing machines,

49:15.720 --> 49:19.440
but you need to feed it things like bearings

49:19.440 --> 49:21.920
or microcontrollers, they can't make those parts.

49:21.920 --> 49:24.440
But other than that, they're making their own things.

49:24.440 --> 49:26.360
And I should note as a footnote,

49:26.360 --> 49:29.600
the stack I described of computers controlling machines

49:29.600 --> 49:32.600
to machine making machines to assemblers to self-assemblers,

49:32.600 --> 49:35.400
view that as fab1234.

49:35.400 --> 49:38.280
So we're transitioning from fab1 to fab2

49:38.280 --> 49:40.640
and the research in the lab is three and four.

49:40.640 --> 49:43.960
At this fab2 stage, a big component of this

49:43.960 --> 49:47.920
is sustainability in the material feedstocks.

49:47.920 --> 49:51.600
So Alicia, colleague in Chile is leading a great effort

49:51.600 --> 49:54.040
looking at how you take forest products

49:54.040 --> 49:55.720
and coffee grounds and seashells

49:55.720 --> 49:58.680
and a range of locally available materials

49:58.680 --> 50:02.520
and produce the high tech materials that go into the lab.

50:02.520 --> 50:05.840
So all of that is machine building today.

50:05.840 --> 50:10.840
Then back in the lab, what we can do today is

50:11.840 --> 50:14.040
we have robots that can build structures

50:14.040 --> 50:17.440
and can assemble more robots that build structures.

50:17.440 --> 50:20.280
We have finer resolution robots

50:20.280 --> 50:22.880
that can build micromechanical systems.

50:22.880 --> 50:26.840
So robots that can build robots that can walk and manipulate.

50:26.840 --> 50:31.920
And we're just now, we have a project at the layer below that

50:31.920 --> 50:33.720
where there's endless attention today

50:33.720 --> 50:37.200
to billion dollar chip fab investments.

50:37.200 --> 50:40.120
But a really interesting thing we pass through

50:40.320 --> 50:44.200
is today the smallest transistors you can buy

50:44.200 --> 50:47.400
as a single transistor, just commercially for electronics,

50:47.400 --> 50:49.760
is actually the size of an early transistor

50:49.760 --> 50:51.840
in an integrated circuit.

50:51.840 --> 50:54.600
So we're using these machines, making machines,

50:54.600 --> 50:57.360
making assemblers to place those parts

50:57.360 --> 50:59.360
to not use a billion dollar chip fab

50:59.360 --> 51:00.520
to make integrated circuits,

51:00.520 --> 51:03.160
but actually assemble little electronic components.

51:03.160 --> 51:06.880
So have a fine enough, precise enough actuators

51:06.920 --> 51:10.200
and manipulators that allow you to place these transistors.

51:10.200 --> 51:12.600
Right, that's a research project in my lab

51:13.600 --> 51:16.360
called DICE on Discrete Assembly of Integrated Electronics.

51:16.360 --> 51:18.920
And we're just at the point to really start

51:18.920 --> 51:20.480
to take seriously this notion

51:20.480 --> 51:24.400
of not having a chip fab make integrated electronics,

51:24.400 --> 51:26.840
but having not a 3D printer,

51:26.840 --> 51:30.120
but a thing that's a cross between a pick in place

51:30.120 --> 51:32.200
makes circuit boards in 2D.

51:32.200 --> 51:34.840
The 3D printer extrudes in 3D.

51:34.880 --> 51:37.040
We're making sort of a micromanipulator

51:37.040 --> 51:38.160
that acts like a printer,

51:38.160 --> 51:41.400
but it's placing to build electronics in 3D.

51:41.400 --> 51:43.440
But this micromanipulator is distributed,

51:43.440 --> 51:45.880
so there's a bunch of them, or is this one centralized thing?

51:45.880 --> 51:47.680
So that's why that's a great question.

51:47.680 --> 51:51.280
So I have a prize that's almost but not been claimed

51:51.280 --> 51:54.680
for the students whose thesis can walk out of the printer.

51:54.680 --> 51:55.640
Oh, nice.

51:55.640 --> 51:59.400
So you have to print the thesis with the means

51:59.400 --> 52:01.560
to exit the printer,

52:01.560 --> 52:05.840
and it has to contain its description of the thesis

52:05.840 --> 52:07.200
that says how to do that.

52:08.240 --> 52:09.760
It's a really good...

52:09.760 --> 52:12.680
I mean, it's a fun example of exactly

52:12.680 --> 52:13.520
the thing we're talking about.

52:13.520 --> 52:17.480
And I've had a few students almost get to that.

52:17.480 --> 52:20.920
And so in what I'm describing,

52:20.920 --> 52:23.400
there's this stack where we're getting closer,

52:23.400 --> 52:26.720
but it's still quite a few years to really go from us.

52:26.720 --> 52:28.840
So there's a layer below the transistors

52:28.840 --> 52:30.520
where we assemble the base materials

52:30.520 --> 52:32.200
that become the transistor.

52:32.200 --> 52:35.600
We're now just at the edge of assembling the transistors

52:35.600 --> 52:37.760
to make the circuits.

52:37.760 --> 52:41.640
We can assemble the micro parts to make the micro robots.

52:41.640 --> 52:43.640
We can assemble the bigger robots.

52:43.640 --> 52:44.600
And in the coming years,

52:44.600 --> 52:47.560
we'll be patching together all of those scales.

52:47.560 --> 52:52.560
So do you see a vision of just endless billions of robots

52:52.680 --> 52:54.920
at the different scales, self-assembling,

52:55.920 --> 52:58.880
self-replicating and building complicated structures?

52:58.880 --> 53:00.520
Yes.

53:00.520 --> 53:03.360
And the but to the yes, but is...

53:03.360 --> 53:04.960
Let me clarify two things.

53:04.960 --> 53:09.960
One is that immediately raises King Charles' fear

53:10.120 --> 53:15.040
of gray goo, of runaway mutant self-reproducing things.

53:15.040 --> 53:17.320
The reason why there are many things

53:17.320 --> 53:19.080
I can tell you to worry about,

53:19.080 --> 53:21.280
but that's not one of them,

53:21.280 --> 53:25.680
is if you want things to autonomously self-reproduce

53:25.680 --> 53:26.800
and take over the world,

53:26.800 --> 53:29.080
that means they need to compete with nature

53:29.080 --> 53:32.960
on using the resources of nature, of water and sunlight.

53:32.960 --> 53:35.640
And in light of everything I'm describing,

53:35.640 --> 53:37.960
biology knows everything I told you.

53:37.960 --> 53:39.560
Every single thing I explained,

53:39.560 --> 53:41.280
biology already knows how to do.

53:43.200 --> 53:45.480
What I'm describing isn't new for biology,

53:45.480 --> 53:47.920
it's new for non-biological systems.

53:47.920 --> 53:50.520
So in the digital era,

53:50.520 --> 53:53.800
the economic when ended up being centralized,

53:53.800 --> 53:55.680
the big platforms.

53:55.680 --> 53:58.320
In this world of machines that can make machines,

53:58.320 --> 53:59.960
I'm asked for example,

54:01.000 --> 54:03.560
what's the killer opportunity?

54:03.560 --> 54:05.640
Who's gonna make all the money?

54:05.640 --> 54:07.120
Who to invest in?

54:07.120 --> 54:09.000
But if the machine can make the machine,

54:09.000 --> 54:12.200
it's not a great business to invest in the machine.

54:13.540 --> 54:17.880
In the same way that if you can think globally,

54:17.880 --> 54:19.760
but produce locally,

54:19.760 --> 54:23.360
then the way the technology goes out into society

54:23.360 --> 54:26.160
isn't a function of central control,

54:26.160 --> 54:27.940
but is fundamentally distributed.

54:27.940 --> 54:31.680
Now, that raises an obvious kind of concern,

54:31.680 --> 54:32.800
which is well, doesn't this mean

54:32.800 --> 54:35.760
you could make bombs and guns and all of that?

54:35.760 --> 54:39.600
The reason that's much less of a problem than you would think

54:39.600 --> 54:42.920
is making bombs and guns and all of that

54:42.920 --> 54:45.280
is a very well-met market need.

54:45.280 --> 54:49.720
Anywhere we go, there's a fine supply chain for weapons.

54:49.720 --> 54:51.840
Now, hobbyists have been making guns for ages

54:51.840 --> 54:54.360
and guns are available just about anywhere.

54:54.360 --> 54:56.360
So you could go into the lab and make a gun.

54:56.360 --> 54:58.440
Today, it's not a very good gun

54:58.440 --> 55:00.160
and guns are easily available.

55:00.160 --> 55:03.240
And so generally, we've run these lab and war zones.

55:03.240 --> 55:08.080
What we find is people don't go to them to make weapons,

55:08.080 --> 55:09.480
which you can already do anyway.

55:09.480 --> 55:11.600
It's an alternative to making weapons.

55:11.600 --> 55:12.800
Coming back to your question,

55:12.800 --> 55:15.880
I'd say the single most important thing I've learned is

55:17.000 --> 55:19.040
the greatest natural resource of the planet

55:19.040 --> 55:23.120
is this amazing density of bright invent of people

55:23.120 --> 55:24.640
whose brains are underused.

55:24.640 --> 55:29.640
And you could view the social engineering of this lab work

55:30.360 --> 55:32.440
is creating the capacity for them.

55:32.440 --> 55:37.120
And so in the end, the way this is gonna impact society

55:37.120 --> 55:38.920
isn't gonna be command and control.

55:38.920 --> 55:41.000
It's how the world uses it.

55:41.000 --> 55:43.560
And it's been really gratifying for me

55:43.560 --> 55:45.800
to see just how it does.

55:45.800 --> 55:48.160
Yeah, but what are the different ways

55:48.160 --> 55:50.920
the evolution of the exponential scaling

55:50.920 --> 55:52.760
of digital fabrication can evolve?

55:52.760 --> 55:56.760
So you said, yeah, self replicating nanobots, right?

55:56.760 --> 55:59.720
This is the gray goo fear.

55:59.720 --> 56:01.800
It's a caricature of a fear,

56:01.800 --> 56:03.720
but nevertheless, there's interesting,

56:03.720 --> 56:06.600
just like you said, spam and all these kinds of things

56:06.600 --> 56:10.080
that came with the scaling of communication and computation.

56:10.080 --> 56:11.920
What are the different ways

56:11.920 --> 56:15.120
that malevolent actors will use this technology?

56:15.120 --> 56:17.680
Yeah, well, first, let me start with a benevolent story,

56:17.720 --> 56:22.720
which is trash is an analog concept.

56:24.000 --> 56:25.800
There's no trash in a forest.

56:25.800 --> 56:28.520
All the parts get disassembled and reused.

56:28.520 --> 56:31.560
Trash means something doesn't have enough information

56:31.560 --> 56:33.960
to tell you how to reuse it.

56:33.960 --> 56:38.400
It's as simple as there's no trash in a Lego room.

56:38.400 --> 56:39.760
When you assemble Lego,

56:39.760 --> 56:42.880
the Lego bricks have enough information to disassemble them.

56:42.880 --> 56:47.320
So as you go through this fab one, two, three, four story,

56:47.320 --> 56:51.200
one of the implications of this transition

56:51.200 --> 56:53.720
to from printing to assembling.

56:53.720 --> 56:56.280
So the real breakthrough technologically

56:56.280 --> 56:58.280
isn't additive versus subtractive,

56:58.280 --> 57:02.400
which is a subject of a lot of attention and hype.

57:02.400 --> 57:04.040
3D printers are useful.

57:05.280 --> 57:07.960
We spun off companies like form labs

57:07.960 --> 57:09.840
led by Max for 3D printing.

57:09.840 --> 57:12.400
But in a fab lab, it's one of maybe 10 machines.

57:12.400 --> 57:15.140
It's used, but it's only part of the machines.

57:15.140 --> 57:18.060
The real technological change is when we go from printing

57:18.060 --> 57:22.220
and cutting to assembling and disassembling.

57:22.220 --> 57:26.580
But that reduces inventories of hundreds of thousands

57:26.580 --> 57:28.260
of parts to just having a few parts

57:28.260 --> 57:29.860
to make almost anything.

57:29.860 --> 57:31.880
It reduces global supply chains

57:31.880 --> 57:34.180
to locally sourcing these building blocks.

57:34.180 --> 57:36.980
But one of the key implications is it gets rid

57:36.980 --> 57:40.820
of technological trash because you can disassemble

57:40.820 --> 57:43.260
and reuse the parts, not throw them away.

57:43.260 --> 57:45.900
And so initially that's of interest for things

57:45.900 --> 57:48.720
at the end of long supply chains, like satellites on orbit.

57:48.720 --> 57:51.700
But one of the things coming is eliminating technical trash

57:51.700 --> 57:54.420
through reuse of the building blocks.

57:54.420 --> 57:56.840
So like when you think about 3D printers,

57:56.840 --> 57:59.960
you're thinking about addition and subtraction

57:59.960 --> 58:03.660
when you think about the other options available to you

58:03.660 --> 58:05.820
in that parameter space as you call it,

58:05.820 --> 58:09.540
that's going to be assembly, this assembly cutting you said.

58:09.540 --> 58:14.540
So the 1952 NC mill was subtractive, you remove material.

58:15.700 --> 58:20.140
And 3D printing additive, and there's a couple of claims

58:20.140 --> 58:21.820
to the invention of 3D printing,

58:21.820 --> 58:23.660
that's closer to what's called net shape,

58:23.660 --> 58:25.500
which is you don't have to cut away the material

58:25.500 --> 58:27.700
you don't need, you just put material where you do need it.

58:27.700 --> 58:30.140
And so that's the 3D printing revolution.

58:30.140 --> 58:34.620
But there are all sorts of limitations on 3D printing

58:34.620 --> 58:38.220
to the kinds of materials you can print,

58:38.220 --> 58:40.420
of kind of functionality you can print.

58:40.420 --> 58:43.620
We're just not going to get to making a,

58:44.940 --> 58:47.860
everything in a cell phone on a single printer,

58:47.860 --> 58:50.160
but I do expect to make everything in a cell phone

58:50.160 --> 58:51.180
with an assembler.

58:51.180 --> 58:54.380
And so instead of printing and cutting technologically,

58:54.380 --> 58:57.780
it's this transition to assembling and disassembling,

58:57.780 --> 59:00.300
going back to Shannon and Van Neumann,

59:00.300 --> 59:03.500
going back to the ribosome four billion years ago.

59:03.500 --> 59:06.420
Now you come to malevolent.

59:06.420 --> 59:09.020
Let me tell you a story about,

59:09.020 --> 59:14.020
I was doing a briefing for the National Academy

59:14.220 --> 59:19.060
of Sciences group that advises the intelligence communities.

59:19.060 --> 59:21.740
And I talked about the kind of research we do.

59:21.740 --> 59:24.940
And at the very end, I showed a little video clip

59:24.940 --> 59:29.660
of Valentina and Ghana making a local girl

59:29.660 --> 59:33.460
making surface mount electronics in the fab lab.

59:33.460 --> 59:36.380
And I showed that to this room full of people.

59:36.380 --> 59:39.140
One of the members of the intelligence community

59:39.140 --> 59:41.180
got up livid and said,

59:41.180 --> 59:44.660
how dare you waste our time showing us a young girl

59:44.660 --> 59:47.540
in an African village making surface mount electronics.

59:47.540 --> 59:51.060
We're looking at, we need to know about disruptive threats

59:51.060 --> 59:52.820
to the future of the United States.

59:53.820 --> 59:56.700
And somebody else got up in the room and yelled at him,

59:56.700 --> 59:59.500
and you idiot, I can't think of anything more important

59:59.500 --> 01:00:01.860
than this, but for two reasons.

01:00:01.860 --> 01:00:06.420
One reason was because if we rely

01:00:06.420 --> 01:00:09.620
on like informational superiority in the battlefield,

01:00:09.620 --> 01:00:12.020
it means other people could get access to it.

01:00:12.020 --> 01:00:15.060
But this intelligence person's point, bless him,

01:00:15.060 --> 01:00:20.060
wasn't that it was getting at the root causes of conflict

01:00:20.100 --> 01:00:22.300
is if this young girl in an African village

01:00:22.300 --> 01:00:25.140
could actually master surface mount electronics,

01:00:25.140 --> 01:00:28.140
it changes some of the most fundamental things

01:00:28.260 --> 01:00:30.980
about recruitment for terrorism,

01:00:33.060 --> 01:00:35.020
impact of economic migration,

01:00:35.020 --> 01:00:36.940
basic assumptions about an economy.

01:00:36.940 --> 01:00:40.700
It's just existential for the future of the planet.

01:00:40.700 --> 01:00:44.780
But we've just lived through a pandemic.

01:00:44.780 --> 01:00:46.460
I would love to linger on this

01:00:46.460 --> 01:00:50.460
because the possibilities that are positive are endless,

01:00:50.460 --> 01:00:52.100
but the possibilities are negative

01:00:52.100 --> 01:00:54.420
are still nevertheless extremely important.

01:00:54.420 --> 01:00:56.540
Well, it's both positive and negative.

01:00:56.540 --> 01:01:01.540
What do you do with a large number of general assemblers?

01:01:01.540 --> 01:01:03.140
Yeah, with the fab lab,

01:01:03.140 --> 01:01:04.940
you could roughly make a bio lab,

01:01:04.940 --> 01:01:06.540
then learn biotechnology.

01:01:06.540 --> 01:01:10.660
Now, that's terrifying because making self-reproducing

01:01:10.660 --> 01:01:14.300
gray goo that outcompetes biology,

01:01:14.300 --> 01:01:17.540
I consider doom because biology knows everything

01:01:17.540 --> 01:01:19.940
I'm describing and is really good at what it does.

01:01:21.380 --> 01:01:25.860
In how to grow almost anything,

01:01:25.900 --> 01:01:28.980
you learn skills in biotechnology

01:01:28.980 --> 01:01:32.860
that let you make serious biological threats.

01:01:32.860 --> 01:01:36.580
And when you combine some of the innovations

01:01:36.580 --> 01:01:38.180
you see with large language models,

01:01:38.180 --> 01:01:40.740
some of the innovations you see with AlphaFold,

01:01:40.740 --> 01:01:44.940
so applications of AI for designing biological systems

01:01:44.940 --> 01:01:48.020
for writing programs,

01:01:48.020 --> 01:01:50.300
which you can have a large language models increasingly.

01:01:50.300 --> 01:01:53.100
So there seems to be an interesting dance here

01:01:53.100 --> 01:01:58.100
of automating the design stage of complex systems using AI.

01:01:58.980 --> 01:02:02.500
And then that's the bits.

01:02:02.500 --> 01:02:05.260
And you can leap now, the innovations you're talking about,

01:02:05.260 --> 01:02:08.580
you can leap from the complex systems in the digital space

01:02:08.580 --> 01:02:12.620
to the printing, to the creation, to the assembly

01:02:13.540 --> 01:02:18.220
at scale of complex systems in the physical space.

01:02:18.220 --> 01:02:20.540
Yeah, so something to be scared about

01:02:20.540 --> 01:02:23.380
is a fab lab can make a biolab,

01:02:23.380 --> 01:02:25.540
a biolab can make biotechnology,

01:02:25.540 --> 01:02:28.980
somebody could learn to make a virus.

01:02:28.980 --> 01:02:30.060
That's scary.

01:02:30.060 --> 01:02:32.860
That's unlike some of the things I said,

01:02:32.860 --> 01:02:34.780
I don't worry about that's something

01:02:34.780 --> 01:02:37.100
I really worry about that is scary.

01:02:37.100 --> 01:02:38.980
Now, how do you deal with that?

01:02:40.580 --> 01:02:45.580
Prior threats we dealt with command and control.

01:02:45.980 --> 01:02:50.980
So like early color copiers had unique codes

01:02:51.940 --> 01:02:53.620
and you could tell which copier made them.

01:02:53.620 --> 01:02:56.420
Eventually you couldn't keep up with that.

01:02:56.420 --> 01:02:59.500
There was a famous meeting at Asilomar

01:02:59.500 --> 01:03:02.580
in the early days of recombinant DNA,

01:03:02.580 --> 01:03:06.500
where that community recognized the dangers

01:03:06.500 --> 01:03:09.780
of what it was doing and put in place a regime

01:03:09.780 --> 01:03:11.260
to help manage it.

01:03:11.260 --> 01:03:14.580
And so that led to the kind of research management.

01:03:14.940 --> 01:03:18.100
MIT has an office that supervises research

01:03:18.100 --> 01:03:19.860
and it works with the national office.

01:03:19.860 --> 01:03:23.500
That works if you can identify who's doing it and where.

01:03:23.500 --> 01:03:26.420
It doesn't work in this world we're describing.

01:03:26.420 --> 01:03:28.900
So anybody could do this anywhere.

01:03:28.900 --> 01:03:33.900
And so what we found is you can't contain this,

01:03:34.660 --> 01:03:37.060
it's already out, you can't forbid

01:03:37.060 --> 01:03:39.260
because there isn't command and control.

01:03:39.260 --> 01:03:41.540
The most useful thing you can do

01:03:41.540 --> 01:03:44.340
is provide incentives for transparency.

01:03:44.580 --> 01:03:48.380
So, but really the heart of what we do is

01:03:48.380 --> 01:03:51.500
you could do this by yourself in a basement

01:03:51.500 --> 01:03:53.900
for nefarious reasons,

01:03:53.900 --> 01:03:56.140
or you could come into a place in the light

01:03:56.140 --> 01:03:57.900
where you get help and you get community

01:03:57.900 --> 01:03:59.580
and you get resources.

01:03:59.580 --> 01:04:02.540
And there's an incentive to do it in the open,

01:04:02.540 --> 01:04:03.500
not in the dark.

01:04:03.500 --> 01:04:06.300
And that might sound naive,

01:04:06.300 --> 01:04:10.220
but in the sort of places we're working,

01:04:10.260 --> 01:04:15.260
so again, bad people do bad things in these places already,

01:04:16.460 --> 01:04:20.780
but providing openness and providing transparency

01:04:20.780 --> 01:04:22.460
is a key part of managing these.

01:04:22.460 --> 01:04:25.860
And so it transitions from regulating risks

01:04:25.860 --> 01:04:30.060
as regulation to soft power to manage them.

01:04:30.060 --> 01:04:32.020
So there's so much potential for good,

01:04:32.020 --> 01:04:35.340
so much capacity for good that Fab Labs

01:04:35.420 --> 01:04:40.420
and the ability and the tools of creation

01:04:41.220 --> 01:04:42.820
really unlock that potential.

01:04:44.260 --> 01:04:48.140
Yeah, and I don't say that as sort of dewy-eyed naive,

01:04:48.140 --> 01:04:51.100
I say that empirically from just years

01:04:51.100 --> 01:04:52.740
of seeing how this plays out in communities.

01:04:52.740 --> 01:04:55.340
I wonder if it's the early days of personal computers though,

01:04:55.340 --> 01:04:57.420
before we get spam, right?

01:04:57.420 --> 01:05:00.700
In the end, most fundamentally,

01:05:01.660 --> 01:05:05.340
literally the mother of all problems

01:05:05.340 --> 01:05:09.820
is who designed us.

01:05:09.820 --> 01:05:13.900
So assume success

01:05:13.900 --> 01:05:15.860
in that we're gonna transition to the machines,

01:05:15.860 --> 01:05:17.060
making the machines,

01:05:17.060 --> 01:05:20.300
and all of these new sort of social systems we're describing

01:05:20.300 --> 01:05:23.660
will help manage them and curate them and democratize them.

01:05:25.620 --> 01:05:28.580
If we close the gap I just let off with

01:05:28.740 --> 01:05:33.580
of 10 to the 10 to 10 to the 18 between Chip Fab and you,

01:05:34.660 --> 01:05:37.820
we're ultimately in marrying communication,

01:05:37.820 --> 01:05:39.340
computation, and fabrication

01:05:39.340 --> 01:05:42.260
gonna be able to create unimaginable complexity.

01:05:44.700 --> 01:05:48.260
And how do you design that?

01:05:48.260 --> 01:05:53.260
And so I'd say the deepest of all questions

01:05:53.860 --> 01:05:57.820
that I've been working on is,

01:05:57.820 --> 01:06:00.540
goes back to the oldest part of our genome.

01:06:00.540 --> 01:06:05.540
So in our genome, what are called Hox genes,

01:06:06.140 --> 01:06:09.700
and these are morphogenes,

01:06:10.620 --> 01:06:15.620
and nowhere in your genome is the number five.

01:06:16.340 --> 01:06:19.580
It doesn't store the fact that you have five fingers.

01:06:19.580 --> 01:06:22.460
What it stores is what's called a developmental program.

01:06:22.460 --> 01:06:24.300
It's a series of steps,

01:06:24.300 --> 01:06:26.820
and the steps have the character of like,

01:06:26.820 --> 01:06:30.460
grow up a gradient or break symmetry.

01:06:30.460 --> 01:06:32.580
And at the end of that developmental program,

01:06:32.580 --> 01:06:34.540
you have five fingers.

01:06:34.540 --> 01:06:39.540
So you are stored not as a body plan,

01:06:41.380 --> 01:06:44.540
but as a growth plan.

01:06:44.540 --> 01:06:46.540
And there's two reasons for that.

01:06:46.540 --> 01:06:49.660
One reason is just compression.

01:06:49.700 --> 01:06:53.980
Billions of genes can place trillions of cells,

01:06:53.980 --> 01:06:57.460
but the much deeper one is evolution

01:06:57.460 --> 01:07:00.420
doesn't randomly perturb.

01:07:00.420 --> 01:07:02.700
Almost anything you did randomly in the genome

01:07:02.700 --> 01:07:06.980
would be fatal or inconsequential, but not interesting.

01:07:06.980 --> 01:07:11.080
But when you modify things in these developmental programs,

01:07:11.080 --> 01:07:14.260
you go from like webs for swimming to fingers,

01:07:14.260 --> 01:07:17.220
or you go from walking to wings for flying.

01:07:17.220 --> 01:07:19.740
It's a space in which search is interesting.

01:07:19.740 --> 01:07:24.740
So this is the heart of the success of AI.

01:07:26.940 --> 01:07:30.700
In part, it was the scaling we talked about a while ago.

01:07:30.700 --> 01:07:33.940
And in part, it was the representations

01:07:33.940 --> 01:07:37.060
for which search is effective.

01:07:38.380 --> 01:07:41.620
AI has found good representations.

01:07:41.620 --> 01:07:43.060
It hasn't found new ways to search,

01:07:43.060 --> 01:07:45.540
but it's found good representations of search.

01:07:45.900 --> 01:07:47.300
You're saying that's what biology,

01:07:47.300 --> 01:07:49.860
that's what evolution has done,

01:07:49.860 --> 01:07:52.580
is creative representations, structures,

01:07:52.580 --> 01:07:56.260
biological structures through which search is effective.

01:07:56.260 --> 01:08:00.340
And so the developmental programs in the genome

01:08:01.140 --> 01:08:05.420
beautifully encapsulate the lessons of AI.

01:08:05.420 --> 01:08:08.700
And it's molecular intelligence.

01:08:08.700 --> 01:08:11.740
It's AI embodied in our genome.

01:08:11.980 --> 01:08:16.500
It's every bit as profound as the cognition in our brain,

01:08:16.500 --> 01:08:20.660
but now this is sort of thinking in molecular thinking

01:08:20.660 --> 01:08:22.460
in how you design.

01:08:22.460 --> 01:08:27.140
And so I'd say the most fundamental problem we're working on

01:08:27.140 --> 01:08:29.740
is it's kind of tautological

01:08:29.740 --> 01:08:33.420
that when you design a phone, you design the phone.

01:08:33.420 --> 01:08:35.340
You represent the design of the phone.

01:08:35.340 --> 01:08:37.380
But that actually fails when you get

01:08:37.380 --> 01:08:40.420
to the sort of complexity that we're talking about.

01:08:40.420 --> 01:08:43.500
And so there's this profound transition to come.

01:08:43.500 --> 01:08:46.300
Once I can have self-reproducing assemblers

01:08:46.300 --> 01:08:48.580
placing 10 to the 18 parts,

01:08:49.420 --> 01:08:54.420
you need to not sort of metaphorically, but create life

01:08:55.220 --> 01:08:58.660
in that you need to learn how to evolve.

01:08:58.660 --> 01:09:01.820
But evolutionary design has a really misleading,

01:09:01.820 --> 01:09:04.460
trivial meaning.

01:09:04.460 --> 01:09:08.500
It's not as simple as you randomly mutate things.

01:09:08.500 --> 01:09:12.100
It's this much more deep embodiment of AI

01:09:12.100 --> 01:09:13.820
and morphogenesis.

01:09:13.820 --> 01:09:17.340
Is there a way for us to continue the kind of evolutionary

01:09:17.340 --> 01:09:19.020
design that led us to this place

01:09:19.020 --> 01:09:21.820
from the early days of bacteria, single cell organism,

01:09:21.820 --> 01:09:24.500
to ribosomes and the 20 amino acids?

01:09:24.500 --> 01:09:26.900
You mean for human augmentation or?

01:09:26.900 --> 01:09:28.060
For life augment.

01:09:28.060 --> 01:09:30.620
I mean, what would you call assemblers

01:09:30.620 --> 01:09:32.620
that are self-replicating and placing parts?

01:09:32.620 --> 01:09:33.460
What is that?

01:09:34.460 --> 01:09:39.460
The dynamic complex things built with digital fabrication.

01:09:39.860 --> 01:09:40.700
What is that?

01:09:40.700 --> 01:09:41.540
That's life.

01:09:41.540 --> 01:09:44.180
Yeah, so ultimately, absolutely,

01:09:45.420 --> 01:09:47.580
if you add up everything I'm talking about,

01:09:47.580 --> 01:09:51.500
it's building up to creating life in non-living materials.

01:09:51.500 --> 01:09:56.100
And I don't view this as copying life.

01:09:56.100 --> 01:09:58.260
I view it as driving life.

01:09:58.260 --> 01:10:00.780
I didn't start from how does biology work

01:10:00.780 --> 01:10:02.660
and then I'm gonna copy it.

01:10:02.700 --> 01:10:05.980
I start from how to solve problems

01:10:05.980 --> 01:10:09.700
and then it leads me to, in a sense, rediscover biology.

01:10:09.700 --> 01:10:13.060
So if we go back to Valentina in Ghana

01:10:13.060 --> 01:10:15.100
making her circuit board,

01:10:15.100 --> 01:10:17.140
she still needs a chip fab very far away

01:10:17.140 --> 01:10:19.900
to make the processor on her circuit board.

01:10:19.900 --> 01:10:22.700
For her to make the processor locally

01:10:22.700 --> 01:10:24.820
for all the reasons we described,

01:10:24.820 --> 01:10:26.980
you actually need the deep things

01:10:26.980 --> 01:10:29.380
we were just talking about.

01:10:29.380 --> 01:10:32.140
And so it really does lead you.

01:10:32.140 --> 01:10:37.140
So there's a wonderful series of books by Gingery.

01:10:38.540 --> 01:10:41.180
Book one is how to make a charcoal furnace

01:10:41.180 --> 01:10:44.700
and at the end of book seven, you have a machine shop.

01:10:44.700 --> 01:10:47.820
So it's sort of how you do your own

01:10:47.820 --> 01:10:50.340
personal industrial revolution.

01:10:50.340 --> 01:10:55.020
ISRU is what NASA calls in situ resource utilization.

01:10:55.020 --> 01:10:56.740
And that's how do you go to a planet

01:10:56.740 --> 01:10:59.860
and create a civilization?

01:10:59.860 --> 01:11:02.820
ISRU has essentially assumed Gingery.

01:11:02.820 --> 01:11:04.860
You go through the industrial revolution

01:11:04.860 --> 01:11:08.540
and you create the inventory of 100,000 resistors.

01:11:08.540 --> 01:11:10.500
What we're finding is the way,

01:11:10.500 --> 01:11:13.660
the minimum building blocks for a civilization

01:11:13.660 --> 01:11:16.900
is roughly 20 parts.

01:11:16.900 --> 01:11:18.780
So what's interesting about the amino acids

01:11:18.780 --> 01:11:20.380
is they're not interesting.

01:11:20.380 --> 01:11:23.780
They're hydrophobic or hydrophilic, basic or acidic.

01:11:23.780 --> 01:11:26.420
They have typical but not extremal properties

01:11:26.420 --> 01:11:29.700
but they're good enough you can combine them to make you.

01:11:29.740 --> 01:11:33.020
So what this is leading towards is technology

01:11:33.020 --> 01:11:36.980
doesn't need enormous global supply chains.

01:11:36.980 --> 01:11:40.180
It just needs about 20 properties you can compose

01:11:40.180 --> 01:11:43.780
to create all technology as the minimum building blocks

01:11:43.780 --> 01:11:45.940
for a technological civilization.

01:11:45.940 --> 01:11:49.460
So there's going to be 20 basic building blocks

01:11:49.460 --> 01:11:52.940
based on which the self-replicating assemblers can work.

01:11:52.940 --> 01:11:55.220
Right, and I say that not philosophically,

01:11:55.220 --> 01:11:58.420
just empirically, sort of that's where it's heading.

01:11:58.420 --> 01:12:01.780
And I like thinking about

01:12:01.780 --> 01:12:04.860
how you bootstrap a civilization on Mars, that problem.

01:12:04.860 --> 01:12:07.260
There's a fun video on bonus material for the movie

01:12:07.260 --> 01:12:10.580
where we're with a neat group of people we talk about it

01:12:10.580 --> 01:12:12.740
because it has really profound implications

01:12:12.740 --> 01:12:15.300
back here on earth about how we live sustainably.

01:12:16.340 --> 01:12:18.740
What does that civilization on Mars looks like

01:12:18.740 --> 01:12:20.940
that's using ISRU,

01:12:20.940 --> 01:12:24.140
that's using these 20 building blocks and does self-assembly?

01:12:24.140 --> 01:12:27.220
Yeah, go through primary secondary tertiary, quaternary.

01:12:28.860 --> 01:12:33.860
You extract properties like conducting, insulating,

01:12:34.060 --> 01:12:39.060
semi-conducting, magnetic, dielectric, flexural.

01:12:40.700 --> 01:12:43.060
These are the kind of roughly 20 properties.

01:12:44.380 --> 01:12:49.380
With those, those are enough for us to assemble logic

01:12:51.140 --> 01:12:53.540
and they're enough for us to assemble actuation.

01:12:54.500 --> 01:12:58.700
With logic and actuation, we can make micro-robots.

01:12:59.780 --> 01:13:03.300
The micro-robots can build bigger robots.

01:13:03.300 --> 01:13:07.620
The bigger robots can then take the building block materials

01:13:07.620 --> 01:13:09.460
and make the structural elements

01:13:09.460 --> 01:13:12.500
that you then do to make construction

01:13:12.500 --> 01:13:14.060
and then you boot up through the stages

01:13:14.060 --> 01:13:16.380
of a technological civilization.

01:13:16.380 --> 01:13:20.540
By the way, where in the span of logic and actuation

01:13:20.540 --> 01:13:22.380
did the sensing come in?

01:13:22.380 --> 01:13:23.500
Oh, I skipped over that.

01:13:23.500 --> 01:13:28.500
But my favorite sensor is a step response.

01:13:28.540 --> 01:13:31.260
So if you just make a step

01:13:31.260 --> 01:13:33.740
and measure the response to the electric field,

01:13:34.900 --> 01:13:37.220
that ranges from user interfaces

01:13:37.220 --> 01:13:40.020
to positioning to material properties.

01:13:40.020 --> 01:13:43.300
And if you do it at higher frequencies, you get chemistry.

01:13:43.300 --> 01:13:45.380
And you can get all of that just from a step

01:13:45.380 --> 01:13:46.860
in an electric field.

01:13:46.860 --> 01:13:51.860
So for example, once you have time resolution in logic,

01:13:51.940 --> 01:13:54.620
something as simple as two electrodes

01:13:54.620 --> 01:13:58.220
let you do amazingly capable sensing.

01:13:58.220 --> 01:14:00.660
So we've been talking about all the work I do.

01:14:00.660 --> 01:14:04.380
There's a story about how it happens.

01:14:04.380 --> 01:14:06.500
Where do ideas come from?

01:14:06.500 --> 01:14:07.540
That's an interesting story.

01:14:07.540 --> 01:14:08.580
Where do ideas come from?

01:14:08.580 --> 01:14:12.180
So I had mentioned Vannevar Bush

01:14:12.180 --> 01:14:16.980
and he wrote a really influential thing

01:14:16.980 --> 01:14:18.540
called the Endless Frontier.

01:14:18.580 --> 01:14:22.260
So science won World War II.

01:14:22.260 --> 01:14:26.380
The more known story is Nuclear Bombs.

01:14:26.380 --> 01:14:28.940
The less well-known story is the Rad Lab.

01:14:28.940 --> 01:14:32.700
So at MIT, an amazing group of people invented radar

01:14:32.700 --> 01:14:35.300
which is really credited as winning the war.

01:14:35.300 --> 01:14:39.500
So after the war, a grand old man from MIT

01:14:39.500 --> 01:14:44.500
and it was charged with science won the war,

01:14:44.780 --> 01:14:48.300
how do we maintain that edge?

01:14:48.300 --> 01:14:51.620
And the report he wrote led to

01:14:51.620 --> 01:14:53.540
the National Science Foundation

01:14:53.540 --> 01:14:55.420
and the modern notion we take for granted

01:14:55.420 --> 01:14:57.140
but didn't really exist before then

01:14:57.140 --> 01:15:01.640
of public funding of research or research agencies.

01:15:02.620 --> 01:15:06.100
In it, he made again what I consider

01:15:06.100 --> 01:15:11.100
an important mistake, which is he described basic research

01:15:11.100 --> 01:15:15.100
leads to applied research, leads to applications,

01:15:15.100 --> 01:15:18.580
leads to commercialization, leads to impact.

01:15:18.580 --> 01:15:22.820
And so we need to invest in that pipeline.

01:15:22.820 --> 01:15:25.980
The reason I considered a mistake

01:15:25.980 --> 01:15:30.920
is almost all of the examples we've been talking about

01:15:30.920 --> 01:15:33.320
in my lab went backwards,

01:15:33.320 --> 01:15:37.580
that the basic research came from applications.

01:15:37.580 --> 01:15:41.660
And further, almost all of the examples

01:15:41.660 --> 01:15:44.980
we've been talking about came fundamentally

01:15:45.020 --> 01:15:46.300
from mistakes.

01:15:46.300 --> 01:15:51.300
So essentially everything I've ever worked on has failed

01:15:53.620 --> 01:15:56.140
but in failing, something better happened.

01:15:56.140 --> 01:16:00.180
So the way I like to describe it is ready, aim, fire

01:16:00.180 --> 01:16:04.620
is you do your homework, you aim carefully

01:16:04.620 --> 01:16:06.980
at a target you want to accomplish.

01:16:06.980 --> 01:16:08.140
And if everything goes right,

01:16:08.140 --> 01:16:10.300
you then hit the target and succeed.

01:16:11.140 --> 01:16:15.140
What I do, you can think of as ready, fire, aim.

01:16:15.140 --> 01:16:18.220
So you do a lot of work to get ready,

01:16:18.220 --> 01:16:19.960
then you close your eyes

01:16:19.960 --> 01:16:22.700
and you don't really think about where you're aiming

01:16:22.700 --> 01:16:24.900
but you look very carefully at where you did aim,

01:16:24.900 --> 01:16:29.060
where you aim after you fire.

01:16:29.060 --> 01:16:31.940
And the reason that's so important is

01:16:33.460 --> 01:16:34.980
if you do ready, aim, fire,

01:16:34.980 --> 01:16:38.540
there's the best you can hope is hit what you aim at.

01:16:38.580 --> 01:16:40.580
So let me give you some examples.

01:16:41.620 --> 01:16:43.580
Because this is a source of great...

01:16:43.580 --> 01:16:45.500
You're full of good lines today.

01:16:45.500 --> 01:16:47.220
...source of great frustration.

01:16:47.220 --> 01:16:51.300
So I mentioned the early quantum computing.

01:16:51.300 --> 01:16:54.740
So quantum computing is this power of using quantum mechanics

01:16:54.740 --> 01:16:56.860
to make computers that for some problems

01:16:56.860 --> 01:17:01.020
are dramatically more powerful than classical computers.

01:17:01.020 --> 01:17:02.780
Before it started,

01:17:02.780 --> 01:17:05.260
there was a really interesting group of people

01:17:05.260 --> 01:17:09.540
who knew a lot about physics and computing

01:17:09.540 --> 01:17:12.620
that were inventing what became quantum computing

01:17:12.620 --> 01:17:14.180
before it was clear anything,

01:17:14.180 --> 01:17:15.620
there was an opportunity there.

01:17:15.620 --> 01:17:18.380
It was just studying how those relate.

01:17:18.380 --> 01:17:21.020
Here's how it fits to the ready, fire, aim,

01:17:21.020 --> 01:17:24.280
in that I was doing really short-term work in my lab

01:17:24.280 --> 01:17:25.980
on shoplifting tags.

01:17:27.580 --> 01:17:30.980
This was really before there was modern RFID.

01:17:30.980 --> 01:17:35.460
And so how you put tags in objects to sense them,

01:17:35.460 --> 01:17:37.540
something we just take for granted commercially.

01:17:37.540 --> 01:17:39.660
And there was a problem of how you can sense

01:17:39.660 --> 01:17:41.540
multiple objects at the same time.

01:17:42.980 --> 01:17:47.980
And so I was studying how you can remotely sense materials

01:17:48.740 --> 01:17:50.300
to make low-cost tags

01:17:50.300 --> 01:17:53.740
that could let you distinguish multiple objects simultaneously.

01:17:53.740 --> 01:17:55.980
To do that, you need non-linearity

01:17:55.980 --> 01:17:58.260
so that the signal is modulated.

01:17:59.260 --> 01:18:02.980
And so I was looking for material sources of non-linearity

01:18:02.980 --> 01:18:07.980
and that led me to look at how nuclear spins interact,

01:18:09.660 --> 01:18:13.060
just for spin resonance,

01:18:13.060 --> 01:18:17.380
the sort of things you use when you go in an MRI machine.

01:18:17.380 --> 01:18:19.460
And so I was studying how to use that.

01:18:19.460 --> 01:18:21.980
And it turns out that it was a bad idea.

01:18:21.980 --> 01:18:26.980
You couldn't remotely use it for shoplifting tags.

01:18:28.380 --> 01:18:31.260
But I realized you could compute.

01:18:31.260 --> 01:18:36.260
And so with a group of colleagues thinking

01:18:36.780 --> 01:18:38.060
about early quantum computing,

01:18:38.060 --> 01:18:39.980
like David D. Vincenzo and Charlie Bennett

01:18:39.980 --> 01:18:43.220
was articulating what are the properties you need to compute?

01:18:43.220 --> 01:18:45.500
And then looking at how to make the tags,

01:18:45.500 --> 01:18:48.300
it turns out the tags were a terrible idea

01:18:48.300 --> 01:18:53.300
for sensing objects in a supermarket checkout.

01:18:54.260 --> 01:18:56.500
But I realized they were computing.

