So McCullough and Pitts made a model of neurons.

01:38:42.980 --> 01:38:47.780
That led to perceptrons that then through a couple

01:38:47.780 --> 01:38:51.180
of boom busts led to deep learning.

01:38:51.180 --> 01:38:53.980
One of the interesting things about that sequence is

01:38:53.980 --> 01:38:57.500
it diverged off so deep neural networks

01:38:57.500 --> 01:39:00.180
used in machine learning,

01:39:00.180 --> 01:39:03.260
diverged from trying to understand how the brain works.

01:39:04.660 --> 01:39:09.100
What makes them work, what's emerged is,

01:39:09.100 --> 01:39:10.780
it's a really interesting story.

01:39:10.780 --> 01:39:13.140
This may be too much of a technical detail,

01:39:13.140 --> 01:39:15.300
but it has to do with function approximation.

01:39:15.300 --> 01:39:18.660
That we talked about exponentials.

01:39:18.660 --> 01:39:23.660
A deep network needs an exponentially larger

01:39:24.140 --> 01:39:27.220
shallow network to do the same function.

01:39:27.220 --> 01:39:29.860
And that exponential is what gives the power

01:39:29.860 --> 01:39:31.500
to deep networks.

01:39:31.500 --> 01:39:34.820
But what's interesting is the sort of lessons

01:39:34.820 --> 01:39:37.460
about building these deep architectures

01:39:37.460 --> 01:39:41.340
and how to train them have really interesting echoes

01:39:41.340 --> 01:39:43.340
to how brains work.

01:39:43.340 --> 01:39:45.340
And there's an interesting conversation

01:39:45.340 --> 01:39:48.220
that's sort of coming back of neuroscientists

01:39:48.220 --> 01:39:50.380
looking over the shoulder of people training

01:39:50.380 --> 01:39:52.780
these deep networks, seeing interesting echoes

01:39:52.780 --> 01:39:56.700
for how the brain works, interesting parallels with it.

01:39:56.700 --> 01:40:01.580
And so I didn't say consciousness, I just said cognition,

01:40:01.580 --> 01:40:05.220
but I don't know any experimental evidence

01:40:05.220 --> 01:40:07.580
that points to anything in neurobiology

01:40:07.580 --> 01:40:10.100
that says we need quantum mechanics.

01:40:10.100 --> 01:40:15.100
And I view the question about whether a large language model

01:40:15.380 --> 01:40:20.380
is conscious as silly in that biology is full of hacks

01:40:28.420 --> 01:40:29.500
and it works.

01:40:30.460 --> 01:40:34.140
There's no evidence we have that there's anything deeper

01:40:34.140 --> 01:40:37.100
going on than just this sort of stacking up

01:40:37.100 --> 01:40:38.420
of hacks in the brain.

01:40:38.420 --> 01:40:40.860
And somehow consciousness is one of the hacks

01:40:40.860 --> 01:40:42.740
or an emergent property of the hacks.

01:40:42.740 --> 01:40:43.580
Absolutely.

01:40:43.580 --> 01:40:47.980
And just numerically, I said big computations now

01:40:47.980 --> 01:40:50.540
have the degrees of freedom of the brain.

01:40:50.540 --> 01:40:53.300
And they're showing a lot of the phenomenology

01:40:53.300 --> 01:40:57.140
of what we think is properties of what a brain can do.

01:40:59.820 --> 01:41:02.420
And I don't see any reason to invoke anything else.

01:41:02.420 --> 01:41:04.940
That makes you wonder what kind of beautiful stuff

01:41:04.940 --> 01:41:06.900
digital fabrication will create.

01:41:06.900 --> 01:41:09.500
If biology created a few hacks on top of which

01:41:09.500 --> 01:41:12.500
consciousness and cognition, some of the things

01:41:12.500 --> 01:41:15.460
we love about human beings was created.

01:41:15.460 --> 01:41:19.980
It makes you wonder what kind of beauty in the complexity

01:41:19.980 --> 01:41:21.940
can create digital fabrication.

01:41:21.940 --> 01:41:23.700
There's an early peek at that,

01:41:23.700 --> 01:41:26.740
which is there's a misleading term,

01:41:26.740 --> 01:41:29.220
which is generative design.

01:41:29.220 --> 01:41:32.820
Generative design is where you don't tell a computer

01:41:32.820 --> 01:41:33.820
how to design something.

01:41:33.820 --> 01:41:36.420
You tell the computer what you want it to do.

01:41:36.420 --> 01:41:38.020
That doesn't work.

01:41:38.020 --> 01:41:40.940
That only works in limited subdomains.

01:41:41.020 --> 01:41:44.060
You can't do really complex functionality that way.

01:41:44.060 --> 01:41:46.100
The one place it's matured, though,

01:41:46.100 --> 01:41:48.580
is topology optimization for structure.

01:41:48.580 --> 01:41:52.260
So let's say you wanted to make a bicycle or a table.

01:41:53.620 --> 01:41:55.860
You describe the loads on it

01:41:55.860 --> 01:41:57.860
and it figures out how to design it.

01:41:57.860 --> 01:42:01.620
And what it makes are beautiful, organic-looking things.

01:42:01.620 --> 01:42:04.500
These are things that look like they grew in a forest.

01:42:04.500 --> 01:42:07.100
And they look like they grew in a forest

01:42:07.100 --> 01:42:08.940
because that's sort of exactly what they are,

01:42:08.940 --> 01:42:12.900
that they're solving the ways of how you handle loads

01:42:12.900 --> 01:42:14.260
in the same way biology does.

01:42:14.260 --> 01:42:16.500
And so you get things that look like trees

01:42:16.500 --> 01:42:17.820
and shells and all of that.

01:42:17.820 --> 01:42:19.980
And so that's a peek at this transition

01:42:19.980 --> 01:42:24.980
from we design to we teach the machines how to design.

