01:53:17.300 --> 01:53:20.020
Here's your mistake, here's what you should have been doing.

01:53:23.740 --> 01:53:26.540
They just sort of say I'm here and get to work.

01:53:26.540 --> 01:53:29.860
And again, I don't know how far this resource goes.

01:53:29.860 --> 01:53:33.780
So I've said, I consider the world's greatest resource,

01:53:33.780 --> 01:53:36.060
this engine, a bright invent of people

01:53:36.060 --> 01:53:39.220
of which we only see a tiny little iceberg of it.

01:53:39.220 --> 01:53:41.100
And everywhere we open these labs,

01:53:41.100 --> 01:53:43.340
they come out of the woodwork, they come.

01:53:43.340 --> 01:53:45.940
We didn't create all these educational programs,

01:53:45.940 --> 01:53:47.740
all these other things I'm describing.

01:53:47.740 --> 01:53:51.180
We tried to partner everywhere with local schools

01:53:51.180 --> 01:53:53.660
and local companies and kept tripping over dysfunction

01:53:53.660 --> 01:53:55.260
and find we had to create the environment

01:53:55.260 --> 01:53:56.820
where people like this can flourish.

01:53:56.820 --> 01:54:00.060
And so I don't know if this is everyone,

01:54:00.060 --> 01:54:02.580
if it's 1% of society, what the fraction is,

01:54:02.580 --> 01:54:05.620
but it's so many orders of magnitude bigger

01:54:05.620 --> 01:54:07.020
than we see it today.

01:54:07.020 --> 01:54:08.380
We've been racing to keep up with it

01:54:08.380 --> 01:54:10.340
to take advantage of that resource.

01:54:10.340 --> 01:54:12.220
Something tells me it's a very large fraction

01:54:12.220 --> 01:54:13.260
of the population.

01:54:13.260 --> 01:54:17.620
I mean, the thing that gives me most hope for the future

01:54:17.620 --> 01:54:18.820
is that population.

01:54:18.820 --> 01:54:21.180
Once a year, this whole lab network meets.

01:54:21.180 --> 01:54:24.100
And it's my favorite gathering, it's in Bhutan this year,

01:54:24.100 --> 01:54:27.820
because it's every body shape, it's every language,

01:54:27.820 --> 01:54:30.020
every geography, but it's the same person

01:54:30.020 --> 01:54:31.700
in all those packages.

01:54:31.700 --> 01:54:36.700
It's the same sense of bright invent of joy and discovery.

01:54:36.940 --> 01:54:38.340
If there's people listening to this

01:54:38.340 --> 01:54:41.700
and they're just overwhelmed with how exciting this is,

01:54:41.700 --> 01:54:44.300
which I think they would be, how can they participate,

01:54:44.300 --> 01:54:47.540
how can they help, how can they encourage young people

01:54:47.540 --> 01:54:50.940
or themselves to build stuff, to create stuff?

01:54:50.940 --> 01:54:51.980
Yeah, that's a great question.

01:54:51.980 --> 01:54:56.980
So this is part of a much bigger maker movement

01:54:58.740 --> 01:55:00.580
that has a lot of embodiments.

01:55:00.580 --> 01:55:03.380
The part I've been involved in, this fab lab network,

01:55:03.380 --> 01:55:06.180
you can think of as a curated part that works as a network.

01:55:06.180 --> 01:55:09.260
So you don't benefit in a gym

01:55:09.260 --> 01:55:11.780
if somebody exercises in another gym,

01:55:11.780 --> 01:55:14.420
but in the fab network, you do, in a sense,

01:55:14.420 --> 01:55:16.780
benefit when somebody works in another network,

01:55:16.780 --> 01:55:19.540
another lab in the way it functions as a network.

01:55:19.540 --> 01:55:23.540
So you can come to cba.mit.edu

01:55:23.540 --> 01:55:26.340
to see the research we're talking about.

01:55:26.340 --> 01:55:29.420
There's a fab foundation run by Sherry Lasseter

01:55:29.420 --> 01:55:31.460
at fabfoundation.org.

01:55:31.460 --> 01:55:35.320
Fab Labs I.O. is a portal into this lab network.

01:55:36.820 --> 01:55:40.020
Fabacademy.org is this distributed hands-on

01:55:40.020 --> 01:55:41.980
educational program.

01:55:41.980 --> 01:55:44.940
Fab.city is the platform of cities producing

01:55:44.940 --> 01:55:45.780
what they consume.

01:55:45.780 --> 01:55:48.620
Those are all nodes in this network.

01:55:48.660 --> 01:55:50.380
So you can learn with Fabacademy

01:55:50.380 --> 01:55:53.060
and you can perhaps launch or help launch

01:55:53.060 --> 01:55:54.700
or participate in launching a fab lab.

01:55:54.700 --> 01:55:59.220
Well, in particular, from one to a thousand,

01:55:59.220 --> 01:56:00.740
we carefully counted labs.

01:56:00.740 --> 01:56:03.100
Now we're going from a thousand to a million

01:56:03.100 --> 01:56:05.340
where it ceases to become interesting to count them.

01:56:05.340 --> 01:56:07.300
And in the thousand to the million,

01:56:08.300 --> 01:56:12.900
what's interesting about that stage is technologically,

01:56:12.900 --> 01:56:15.300
you go to a lab not to get access to the machine,

01:56:15.300 --> 01:56:17.940
but you go to the lab to make the machine.

01:56:17.940 --> 01:56:20.220
But the other thing interesting in it

01:56:20.220 --> 01:56:22.620
is we have an interesting collaboration

01:56:22.620 --> 01:56:26.460
on a fab lab in a box.

01:56:26.460 --> 01:56:30.740
And this came out of a collaboration with SolidWorks

01:56:30.740 --> 01:56:34.980
on how you can put a fab lab in a box,

01:56:34.980 --> 01:56:37.820
which is not just the tools, but the knowledge.

01:56:37.820 --> 01:56:42.100
So you open the box and the box contains the knowledge

01:56:42.100 --> 01:56:45.660
of how to use it as well as the tools within it

01:56:45.660 --> 01:56:47.340
so that the knowledge can propagate.

01:56:47.340 --> 01:56:48.860
And so we have an interesting group of people

01:56:48.860 --> 01:56:52.020
working on the original fab labs.

01:56:52.020 --> 01:56:54.020
We have a whole team to get involved

01:56:54.020 --> 01:56:56.300
in the setting up and training.

01:56:56.300 --> 01:56:58.740
And the Fabacademy is a real in-depth,

01:56:58.740 --> 01:57:01.100
deep technical program in the training.

01:57:01.100 --> 01:57:05.020
But in this next phase, how sort of the lab itself

01:57:05.020 --> 01:57:06.220
knows how to do the lab.

01:57:09.100 --> 01:57:13.060
We've talked deeply about the intelligence in fabrication,

01:57:13.060 --> 01:57:14.620
but in a much more accessible one

01:57:14.620 --> 01:57:19.540
about how the AI in the lab in effect

01:57:19.540 --> 01:57:23.380
becomes a collaborator with you in this nearer term

01:57:23.380 --> 01:57:24.500
to help get started.

01:57:24.500 --> 01:57:28.380
And for people wanting to connect,

01:57:28.380 --> 01:57:31.140
it can seem like a big step, a big threshold,

01:57:31.140 --> 01:57:32.940
but we've gotten to thousands of these

01:57:32.940 --> 01:57:35.300
and they're doubling exactly that way

01:57:35.300 --> 01:57:37.660
just from people opting in.

01:57:37.660 --> 01:57:40.540
And in so doing, driving towards this kind of idea

01:57:40.540 --> 01:57:43.900
of personal digital fabrication.

01:57:44.220 --> 01:57:46.580
And it's not utopia, it's not free,

01:57:46.580 --> 01:57:51.580
but come back to today, we separately have education,

01:57:52.580 --> 01:57:55.540
we have big business, we have startups,

01:57:55.540 --> 01:57:59.700
we have entertainment, each of these things are segregated.

01:57:59.700 --> 01:58:01.940
When you have global connection

01:58:01.940 --> 01:58:04.140
to one of these local facilities,

01:58:04.140 --> 01:58:07.820
in that you can do play and art and education

01:58:07.820 --> 01:58:09.460
and create infrastructure.

01:58:10.660 --> 01:58:13.700
You can make many of the things you consume.

01:58:13.700 --> 01:58:14.980
You could make it for yourself,

01:58:14.980 --> 01:58:16.740
it could be done on a community scale,

01:58:16.740 --> 01:58:19.140
it could be done on a regional scale.

01:58:20.300 --> 01:58:24.260
It really, I'd say the research we spent

01:58:24.260 --> 01:58:27.740
the last few hours talking about, I thought was hard.

01:58:27.740 --> 01:58:32.740
And in a sense, I mean, it's non-trivial

01:58:32.740 --> 01:58:35.300
but in a sense, it's just sort of playing out

01:58:35.300 --> 01:58:36.500
we're turning the crank.

01:58:36.500 --> 01:58:39.100
What I didn't think was hard is

01:58:40.300 --> 01:58:42.900
if anybody can make almost anything anywhere,

01:58:43.700 --> 01:58:45.500
how do you live, how do you learn,

01:58:45.500 --> 01:58:47.460
how do you work, how you play,

01:58:47.460 --> 01:58:50.980
these very basic assumptions about how society functions.

01:58:50.980 --> 01:58:54.820
There's a way in which it's kind of back to the future

01:58:54.820 --> 01:58:59.820
in that this mode where work is money is consumption

01:59:00.020 --> 01:59:03.660
and consumption is shopping by selecting

01:59:03.660 --> 01:59:07.380
is only a kind of a few decade old stretch.

01:59:08.900 --> 01:59:13.020
In some ways, we're getting back to a Sami village

01:59:13.020 --> 01:59:17.300
in North Norway is deeply sustainable,

01:59:18.460 --> 01:59:22.060
but rather than just reverting to living

01:59:22.060 --> 01:59:24.320
the way we did a few thousand years ago,

01:59:25.580 --> 01:59:28.760
being connected globally, having the benefits

01:59:28.760 --> 01:59:32.020
of modern society, but connecting it back

01:59:32.020 --> 01:59:34.500
to older notions of sustainability.

01:59:35.740 --> 01:59:40.020
I hadn't remotely anticipated just how fundamentally

01:59:40.020 --> 01:59:42.980
that challenges how a society functions.

01:59:42.980 --> 01:59:46.300
And how interesting and how hard it is to figure out

01:59:46.300 --> 01:59:47.900
how we can make that work.

01:59:47.900 --> 01:59:50.540
And it's possible that this kind of process

01:59:51.500 --> 01:59:54.940
will give a deeper sense of meaning to each person.

01:59:54.940 --> 01:59:58.180
Let me violently agree in two ways.

01:59:58.180 --> 02:00:03.180
One way is this community making

02:00:05.380 --> 02:00:09.460
crosses many sensitive sectarian boundaries

02:00:09.460 --> 02:00:11.900
in many parts of the world where there's just,

02:00:13.380 --> 02:00:15.660
implicit or explicit conflict,

02:00:15.660 --> 02:00:20.660
but sort of this act of making seems to transcend

02:00:21.020 --> 02:00:22.740
a lot of historical divisions.

02:00:22.740 --> 02:00:24.460
I don't say that philosophically,

02:00:24.460 --> 02:00:26.420
I just say that as an observation.

02:00:26.420 --> 02:00:30.020
And I think there's something really fundamental

02:00:30.020 --> 02:00:34.020
in what you said, which is deep in our brain

02:00:34.020 --> 02:00:35.980
is shaping our environment.

02:00:39.420 --> 02:00:41.900
A lot of what's strange about our society

02:00:41.900 --> 02:00:44.100
is the way that we can't do that.

02:00:45.460 --> 02:00:49.020
The act of shaping our environment

02:00:49.020 --> 02:00:51.260
touches something really, really deep

02:00:51.260 --> 02:00:53.980
that gets to the essence of who we are.

02:00:55.100 --> 02:00:57.820
That's again why I say that in a way,

02:00:57.820 --> 02:01:00.260
the most important thing made in these labs

02:01:00.260 --> 02:01:01.500
is making itself.

02:01:02.740 --> 02:01:06.300
What do you think if the shaping of our environment

02:01:06.300 --> 02:01:07.260
gets to something deep?

02:01:07.260 --> 02:01:09.660
What do you think is the meaning of it all?

02:01:09.660 --> 02:01:11.260
What's the meaning of life, Neil?

02:01:12.220 --> 02:01:17.220
I can tell you my insights into how life works.

02:01:17.660 --> 02:01:19.620
I can tell you my insights

02:01:19.620 --> 02:01:23.820
in how to make life meaningful and fulfilling

02:01:25.460 --> 02:01:26.740
and sustainable.

02:01:29.060 --> 02:01:31.340
I have no idea what the meaning of life is,

02:01:31.340 --> 02:01:33.740
but maybe that's the meaning of life.

02:01:33.740 --> 02:01:35.860
Naha, the uncertainty, the confusion.

02:01:37.020 --> 02:01:38.860
Because there's a magic to it all.

02:01:38.860 --> 02:01:40.140
Everything you've talked about

02:01:40.180 --> 02:01:42.940
from starting from the basic elements

02:01:42.940 --> 02:01:45.420
with the big bang that somehow created the sun

02:01:45.420 --> 02:01:49.220
that somehow set a few to thermodynamics

02:01:49.220 --> 02:01:52.740
and created life in all the ways that you've talked about

02:01:52.740 --> 02:01:54.860
from ribosomes that created the machinery

02:01:54.860 --> 02:01:55.980
that created the machine

02:01:55.980 --> 02:01:59.140
and then now the biological machine creating

02:01:59.140 --> 02:02:00.420
through digital fabrication,

02:02:00.420 --> 02:02:02.420
more complex artificial machines,

02:02:02.420 --> 02:02:05.860
all of that, there's a magic to that creative process.

02:02:05.860 --> 02:02:09.540
And we humans are smart enough to notice the magic.

02:02:09.540 --> 02:02:13.220
So you haven't said the S word yet.

02:02:13.220 --> 02:02:14.060
Which one is that?

02:02:14.060 --> 02:02:14.900
Singularity.

02:02:14.900 --> 02:02:19.700
Yeah, I'm not sure if Ray Kurzweil is listening

02:02:19.700 --> 02:02:20.700
if he is high Ray,

02:02:20.700 --> 02:02:23.220
but I have a complex relationship with Ray

02:02:23.220 --> 02:02:28.220
because a lot of the things he projects, I find annoying,

02:02:28.660 --> 02:02:31.740
but then he does his homework

02:02:31.740 --> 02:02:33.820
and then somewhat annoyingly,

02:02:33.820 --> 02:02:35.980
he points out how almost everything I'm doing

02:02:35.980 --> 02:02:37.860
fits on his roadmaps.

02:02:39.820 --> 02:02:44.820
And so the question is,

02:02:45.420 --> 02:02:47.540
are we heading towards a singularity?

02:02:49.020 --> 02:02:52.980
So I'd have to say I lean towards sigmoids

02:02:52.980 --> 02:02:54.700
rather than exponentials.

02:02:56.340 --> 02:02:59.020
But we've done pretty well with sigmoids.

02:02:59.020 --> 02:03:02.460
Yeah, so sigmoids are things grow and they taper

02:03:02.460 --> 02:03:04.820
and then there can be one after it and one after it.

02:03:04.820 --> 02:03:09.820
So I'll pass on whether there's enough of them

02:03:10.380 --> 02:03:13.020
that they diverge,

02:03:13.020 --> 02:03:18.020
but the selfish gene answer to the meaning of life

02:03:19.900 --> 02:03:23.900
is the meaning of life is the propagation of life.

02:03:23.900 --> 02:03:28.900
And so it was a step for atoms to assemble into a molecule,

02:03:28.900 --> 02:03:33.100
for atoms to assemble into a molecule,

02:03:34.020 --> 02:03:38.580
for molecules to assemble into a proto cell,

02:03:38.580 --> 02:03:41.860
for the proto cell to form, to then form organelles,

02:03:41.860 --> 02:03:44.540
for the organ cells to form organs,

02:03:44.540 --> 02:03:46.660
the organs to form an organism.

02:03:46.660 --> 02:03:51.180
Then it was a step for organisms to form family units,

02:03:51.180 --> 02:03:53.460
then family units to form villages.

02:03:53.460 --> 02:03:56.180
You can view each of those as a stack

02:03:56.180 --> 02:03:57.540
and the level of organization.

02:03:57.540 --> 02:04:02.100
So you could view everything we've spoken about

02:04:02.100 --> 02:04:06.500
as the imperative of life,

02:04:07.660 --> 02:04:10.100
just the next step in the hierarchy of that

02:04:10.100 --> 02:04:12.580
in the fulfillment of the inexorable drive

02:04:12.580 --> 02:04:14.380
of the violation of thermodynamics.

02:04:14.380 --> 02:04:17.980
So you could view, I'm an embodiment of the will

02:04:17.980 --> 02:04:20.340
of the violation of thermodynamics speaking.

02:04:21.980 --> 02:04:24.780
The two of us having an old chat, yes.

02:04:24.780 --> 02:04:25.900
Yeah.

02:04:25.900 --> 02:04:29.020
And so it continues and even then the singularity

02:04:29.020 --> 02:04:31.500
is just a transition up the ladder.

02:04:31.500 --> 02:04:34.540
There's nothing deeper to consciousness

02:04:34.540 --> 02:04:39.540
than it's a derived property of distributed problem solving.

02:04:41.380 --> 02:04:44.020
There's nothing deeper to life

02:04:44.020 --> 02:04:49.020
than embodied AI in morphogenesis.

02:04:50.460 --> 02:04:53.860
So why so much of this conversation in my life

02:04:53.900 --> 02:04:57.260
is involved in these fab labs.

02:04:57.260 --> 02:05:00.020
And initially it just started as outreach,

02:05:00.020 --> 02:05:02.620
then it started as keeping up with it.

02:05:02.620 --> 02:05:05.020
Then it turned to,

02:05:07.820 --> 02:05:09.380
it was rewarding.

02:05:09.380 --> 02:05:12.820
Then it turned to we're learning as much from these labs

02:05:12.820 --> 02:05:14.260
in as goes out to them.

02:05:14.260 --> 02:05:16.700
It began as outreach, but now more knowledge

02:05:16.700 --> 02:05:19.420
is coming back from the labs that is going into them.

02:05:19.420 --> 02:05:24.420
And then finally it ends with what I described

02:05:25.340 --> 02:05:27.140
as competing with myself at MIT,

02:05:27.140 --> 02:05:30.220
but a better way to say that is tapping

02:05:30.220 --> 02:05:31.840
the brain power of the planet.

02:05:33.200 --> 02:05:35.340
And so I guess for me personally,

02:05:35.340 --> 02:05:37.620
that's the meaning of my life.

02:05:37.620 --> 02:05:39.700
And maybe that's the meaning for the universe too.

02:05:39.700 --> 02:05:44.700
It's using us humans and our creations to understand itself

02:05:45.660 --> 02:05:50.060
in the way it's whatever the creative process

02:05:50.060 --> 02:05:53.220
